{"id":"1906.06865","submitter":"Wei Li","authors":"Wei Li, Le Wang, Shengmei Zhao","title":"Phase Matching Quantum Key Distribution based on Single-Photon\n  Entanglement","comments":"7 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Two time-reversal quantum key distribution (QKD) schemes are the quantum\nentanglement based device-independent (DI)-QKD and\nmeasurement-device-independent (MDI)-QKD. The recently proposed twin field\n(TF)-QKD, also known as phase-matching (PM)-QKD, has improved the key rate\nbound from $O\\left( \\eta \\right )$ to $O\\left( \\sqrt {\\eta} \\right )$ with\n$\\eta$ the channel transmittance. In fact, TF-QKD is a kind of MDI-QKD but\nbased on single-photon detection. In this paper, we propose a different PM-QKD\nbased on single-photon entanglement, referred to as single-photon\nentanglement-based phase-matching (SEPM)-QKD, which can be viewed as a\ntime-reversed version of the TF-QKD. Detection loopholes of the standard Bell\ntest, which often occur in DI-QKD over long transmission distances, are not\npresent in this protocol because the measurement settings and key information\nare the same quantity which is encoded in the local weak coherent state. We\ngive a security proof of SEPM-QKD and demonstrate in theory that it is secure\nagainst all collective attacks and beam-splitting attacks. The simulation\nresults show that the key rate enjoys a bound of $O\\left( \\sqrt {\\eta} \\right\n)$ with respect to the transmittance. SEPM-QKD not only helps us understand\nTF-QKD more deeply, but also hints at a feasible approach to eliminate\ndetection loopholes in DI-QKD for long-distance communications.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 17 Jun 2019 06:46:25 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 18 Jun 2019 09:57:27 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 19 Jun 2019 01:22:11 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Thu, 20 J